  "prompt": "Are there statutes that address money laundering?",
  "response": "Yes, there are several statutes that address money laundering in the United States:\n\n1. Federal Level Statutes:\n- Bank Secrecy Act (BSA)\n- Title 18 U.S. Code Section 1956 (Money Laundering Control Act)\n- Title 18 U.S. Code Section 1957\n- Patriot Act of 2001\n\n2. State Level Statutes:\n- Most states have their own money laundering prevention laws\n- These often mirror federal statutes but can have unique provisions\n\n3. Key Provisions:\n- Criminalize financial transactions involving proceeds from illegal activities\n- Require financial institutions to report suspicious transactions\n- Establish reporting requirements for cash transactions over $10,000\n- Impose criminal penalties and potential asset forfeiture\n\n4. Enforcement Agencies:\n- Financial Crimes Enforcement Network (FinCEN)\n- Department of Justice\n- Internal Revenue Service (IRS)\n- Federal Bureau of Investigation (FBI)\n\nThese statutes aim to prevent criminals from disguising illegally obtained funds as legitimate income and to track and prosecute such financial crimes.",
